Violin Plot¶

In [168]:
plt.subplots(figsize= (16, 8))
violin_not_distracted = sns.violinplot(x='abbrev', y='alcohol', data=ds, inner='stick')
violin_not_distracted.set(xlabel='State (Abbreviation)', ylabel='Alcohol Consumption', title = ('Violin Plot: Alcohol Consumption by State with Not Distracted'))
Out[168]:
[Text(0.5, 0, 'State (Abbreviation)'),
 Text(0, 0.5, 'Alcohol Consumption'),
 Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Violin Plot: Alcohol Consumption by State with Not Distracted')]

Each violin-shaped representation corresponds to a state. The width and shape of these "violins" indicate the density of alcohol consumption at various levels within each state. Wider sections indicate higher density or prevalence of certain alcohol consumption levels in that state.

alcohol_scatter.set(title= "alcohol consumption vs total car crashes")
Out[136]:

i) From the speeding vs total car crashes plot, we are unable to judege or come to a conclusion of car crashes with increasing speeds due to the non linearity in the graph

ii)From the alcohol vs total car crashes plot, we can say that as consuption content of alcohol increases the probability is more that the car leads to a crash

Box plot¶

In [108]:

Out[108]:
<Axes: xlabel='speeding', ylabel='total'>

From the above boxplot, the top quantile (upper whisker) is indicating max accidents nearly (15) and the bottom quantile(lower whisker) min accidents nearly (11) and the box which indicates half of the plot i.e 50% indicates median to be (~12.8) and the remaining lines indicate the outliers.

From bothe above box plots it clearly shows that more car crashes are occuring due to alcohol consumption than speeding.

Findings from the correlation heatmap

1) people not involved in any previous accidents and total car accidents columns have a stong positive correlation of 0.96 - Primary Focus

2) The next medium correlation is between the "% of fatalities due to speeding" and the "% of fatalities due to non-distracted" with a value of 0.59. All other correlation can be ignored as they aren't significant enough

Vertical bar plot¶

In [123]:
plt.figure(figsize=(12,10))
d1 = ds[["abbrev",'total','speeding','alcohol','not_distracted','no_previous','ins_premium','ins_losses']].sort_values(by="ins_premium").tail(10)
barp = sns.barplot(x=d1['abbrev'], y=d1['ins_premium'])
barp.set(xlabel= 'State', ylabel = 'car_insurance_premiums', title= 'costliest car_insurance_premiums top 10 states')
Out[123]:
[Text(0.5, 0, 'State'),
 Text(0, 0.5, 'car_insurance_premiums'),
 Text(0.5, 1.0, 'costliest car_insurance_premiums top 10 states')]

Findings from the above plot

1) In general high car insurance premiums in a particular state indicates that there are more high risk of accidents in that state is more which results in costing the insurance company more. Thus the insurance is priced high so as to reduce the loss.

2) Louisiana and New Jersey have the highest car insurance premium (~1300 USD) when compared to the national average of (886.57 USD) indicating these states have high risk drivers.
